AB  - This paper examines the role of debt contracts and intangible capital in the transmission of monetary policy to firm-level investment. Based on an analysis of US non-financial firm-level data, we find that, in response to a contractionary monetary shock, cash flow-based borrowers with a relatively higher proportion of intangible assets experience a sharper contraction in investment than others. However, for asset-based borrowers, firms’ investment responses to monetary policy shocks do not vary with the proportion of intangible assets. A heterogeneous firm model, which features the coexistence of multiple debt contracts and investment portfolio choices, can explain our empirical findings.
